{"title_page": "Michael D. Aeschliman", "text_new": "'''Michael D. Aeschliman''' (born 21 February 1948), is a U.S.-Swiss educator, literary critic and scholar, Professor Emeritus at Boston University, Professor of Anglophone Culture at the ''Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana'' (University of Italian Switzerland)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/wheelock/profile/michael-aeschliman/|title=Michael Aeschliman &#124; Wheelock College of Education & Human Development|website=www.bu.edu}}</ref> and Curriculum Advisor to the American School in Switzerland (TASIS) Foundation Board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tasis.com/page.cfm?p=276|title=TASIS The American School in Switzerland: Dr. Michael D. Aeschliman|website=www.tasis.com}}</ref> He previously taught at the University of Virginia (1985\u20131993).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/Departments/Italian_Studies/LD/numbers/02/aeschliman.html|title=Aeschliman: The Heirs of Canto III of Dante's Inferno|website=www.brown.edu}}</ref> Aeschliman holds B.A., M.A., M.Phil., and Ph.D. degrees from Columbia University. He is the author of ''The Restoration of Man: C. S. Lewis and the Continuing Case against Scientism'' (3rd. edition, 2019; translated into French, 2020), which has been described by ''The National Review'' as \"a book marked by tremendous learning worn lightly, deployed vigorously, and offered generously to a generation that has forgotten how to think because it has lost its grip on the meaning of words.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/magazine/2019/09/30/c-s-lewis-and-the-religion-of-science/|title=C. S. Lewis and the Religion of Science|date=September 12, 2019}}</ref> The major French daily newspaper ''Le Figaro'' also hailed its publication, describing it as a work that \"at long last makes accessible to the general reading public the essential reflections of C. S. Lewis on scientism and transhumanism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/vox/culture/quand-l-auteur-de-narnia-ecrivait-contre-le-transhumanisme-20200306|title=Quand l\u2019auteur de Narnia \u00e9crivait contre le transhumanisme|first=Paul|last=Sugy|date=March 6, 2020|website=Le Figaro.fr}}</ref> The first edition was prefaced by the prominent journalist and intellectual Malcolm Muggeridge and praised by Russell Kirk as \u201cOne of the most perceptive books on C. S. Lewis,\u201d and \u201cA succinct, strong book, worthy of Lewis himself.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://evolutionnews.org/2019/09/from-national-review-a-rave-for-aeschliman-on-the-religion-of-science/|title=From National Review, a Rave for Aeschliman on the \"Religion of Science\"|date=September 17, 2019|website=Evolution News}}</ref> Aeschliman writes regularly on educational and cultural topics for several American magazines, including ''National Review'', ''First Things'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstthings.com/article/1990/08/solzhenitsyn-and-modern-literature|title=Solzhenitsyn and Modern Literature &#124; M. D. Aeschliman|website=First Things}}</ref> ''Modern Age'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isi.org/modern-age/faustian-fantasist-and-fraud/|title=Faustian, Fantasist, and Fraud|date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> and ''The Journal of Education'' (Boston).<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/42742591|title=Enduring Documents and Public Doctrines: Martin Luther King's \"Letter from Birmingham Jail\" after Forty Years|author=Aeschliman, Micheal D.|year=2005|journal=The Journal of Education|volume=186|issue=1|pages=29\u201346|via=JSTOR}}</ref> He is featured in the film \"The Magician's Twin: C.S. Lewis and the Case against Scientism\" (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discovery.org/v/the-magicians-twin/|title=The Magician's Twin|website=Discovery Institute}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.movieguide.org/reviews/the-magicians-twin.html|title=THE MAGICIAN\u2019S TWIN &#124; Movieguide &#124; Movie Reviews for Christians|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref> In 2012, Aeschliman authored a new critical edition of Charles Dickens' ''A Tale of Two Cities''.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Tale-Cities-Ignatius-Critical-Editions/dp/1586174428</ref>[[Category:Literary Criticism]][[Category:C. S. Lewis]][[Category:Scientism]][[Category:Christianity]][[Category:Education]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "'''Michael D. Aeschliman''' (born 21 February 1948), is a U.S.-Swiss educator, literary critic and scholar, Professor Emeritus at Boston University, Professor of Anglophone Culture at the ''Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana'' (University of Italian Switzerland)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/wheelock/profile/michael-aeschliman/|title=Michael Aeschliman &#124; Wheelock College of Education & Human Development|website=www.bu.edu}}</ref> and Curriculum Advisor to the American School in Switzerland (TASIS) Foundation Board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tasis.com/page.cfm?p=276|title=TASIS The American School in Switzerland: Dr. Michael D. Aeschliman|website=www.tasis.com}}</ref> He previously taught at the University of Virginia (1985\u20131993).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/Departments/Italian_Studies/LD/numbers/02/aeschliman.html|title=Aeschliman: The Heirs of Canto III of Dante's Inferno|website=www.brown.edu}}</ref> Aeschliman holds B.A., M.A., M.Phil., and Ph.D. degrees from Columbia University. He is the author of ''The Restoration of Man: C. S. Lewis and the Continuing Case against Scientism'' (3rd. edition, 2019; translated into French, 2020), which has been described by ''The National Review'' as \"a book marked by tremendous learning worn lightly, deployed vigorously, and offered generously to a generation that has forgotten how to think because it has lost its grip on the meaning of words.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/magazine/2019/09/30/c-s-lewis-and-the-religion-of-science/|title=C. S. Lewis and the Religion of Science|date=September 12, 2019}}